///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////8. What is Concurrency Handling in EF Core?
 Definition (Very Easy Explanation)

Imagine two people (say you and your friend) trying to edit the same house record at the same time in your Buy & Sell Property App.

You change the price to ₹50,00,000

Your friend changes it to ₹55,00,000 at the same time


Now… who should win? 🤔
That’s where Concurrency Handling comes in — it helps detect and manage conflicts when multiple users update the same data at once.


---

⚙️ How EF Core Handles It (Simple Technical View)

EF Core uses a Concurrency Token (like a timestamp or version number) to detect if a record was changed after you loaded it.

Example:

When EF Core loads a record, it remembers the original version.

When you update, EF checks:

> “Is this record still the same as when I read it?”



If someone else has modified it, EF will throw a DbUpdateConcurrencyException.



---

💻 Example Code

public class Property
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }

    [Timestamp] // 👈 This helps EF detect concurrency conflicts
    public byte[] RowVersion { get; set; }
}

// When updating:
try
{
    _context.Update(property);
    await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
}
catch (DbUpdateConcurrencyException)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Someone else already updated this property. Please refresh and try again.");
}


---

🏠 Project Use (Buy & Sell Property App)

In your Buy & Sell Property App, concurrency handling is useful when:

Two sellers try to update the same property listing at the same time.

You need to prevent overwriting each other’s changes.

It ensures data accuracy (like correct price or address).


Example:

> If a user tries to edit an outdated property detail, EF Core warns the user to reload the latest data before saving.




---

⚖️ Trade-offs

✅ Pros ⚠️ Cons

Prevents data conflicts Adds extra database check
Ensures data integrity Slightly slower for bulk updates
Increases reliability Needs exception handling code


